  "text": "Sections (thickness, 3 mm) were stained with hematoxylin and eosin, Brown and Brenn, Brown-Hopps, Wolbach's Giemsa, Verhoeff elastic, and Steiner silver stains and were tested specifically for B. pertussis with use of an immunoalkaline phophatase technique. The primary monoclonal antibody (1H2; isotype IgG2a) used in the IHC assay reacts with the lipooligosaccharide A of B. pertussis and was used at a dilution of 1:1000. The specificity of this antibody was evaluated with use of formalin-fixed, paraffin-embedded culture specimens of 4 geographically and temporally distinct strains of B. pertussis (E144, E161, E194, and D946), [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The occurrence of each histopathologic feature was compared between the group of infants with B. pertussis as their only identified infecting pathogen and infants with infection due to B. pertussis and у1 other pathogen with use of the 2-sided Fisher's exact test. A P value !.05 was considered to be statistically significant. Molecular analyses. DNA was extracted from one 10-mm section of lung or upper airway tissue from each patient [CITATION_3] and was eluted in a final volume of 100 mL. Ten microliters of extract was evaluated by a conventional PCR assay that amplifies a segment of the IS481 sequence of B. pertussis with use of primers IS481F and IS481R [CITATION_4] . A real-time PCR assay was also used to amplify a 55-base pair segment of the B. pertussis toxin gene (ptxS1). The amplification mixture for the real-time assay contained 3 mL of extracted DNA in a 17-mL mixture containing 700 nmol each of primers 402U16 and 442L15, 300 nmol of probe 419U22P, and 0.8 mL of dimethylsulfoxide (K.-H.W., unpublished data). Tissue extracts were also evaluated for DNA of B. parapertussis with a real-time PCR assay designed to amplify a segment of the IS1001 sequence with use of primers Bpp-F1 and Bpp-R1 [CITATION_5] . All amplicons of the appropriate sizes were sequenced. Sequence similarities were determined by the BLAST program.",
